  "body": "Hello:\r\n\r\nI am trying to get solc, using https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/wiki/Contract-Tutorial#using-an-online-compiler as a guide. \r\nI first did \r\n`brew install cpp-ethereum`\r\n`brew linkapps cpp-ethereum`\r\n`which solc`\r\nThe brew install seems to have worked, but `which solc` returned nothing. \r\n\r\nI thence tried another way (compiling from source):\r\n`git clone https://github.com/ethereum/cpp-ethereum.git`\r\n`mkdir cpp-ethereum/build`\r\n`cd cpp-ethereum/build`\r\n`cmake -DJSONRPC=OFF -DMINER=OFF -DETHKEY=OFF -DSERPENT=OFF -DGUI=OFF -DTESTS=OFF -DJSCONSOLE=OFF ..`\r\n`make -j4`\r\n`make install`\r\n`which solc`\r\n\r\nAgain, apart from some warnings, no error popped up. But again, unfortunately, `which solc`returns nothing. Looking for a directory called solc also returns nothing.\r\n\r\n**So I failed to install solc. How can I do that?** \r\n\r\nSomething else surprises me. I installed Truffle. Using `truffle test` on the mock contract Truffle provides works all right, i.e., i believe the contract is compiled. I thought Truffle used solc to compiler contracts... without solc on my system, how comes Truffle can compile? \r\n\r\nRgds\r\n#### System information\r\n\r\n**Geth version:** \r\nVersion: 1.4.16-stable-68815256\r\nProtocol Versions: [63 62]\r\nNetwork Id: 1\r\nGo Version: go1.7.1\r\nOS: darwin\r\nGOPATH=\r\nGOROOT=/usr/local/Cellar/go/1.7.1/libexec\r\n**OS & Version:** OSX el capitan\r\n",
